fields.value: Replication Data for: The war that wasn't there? Framing Italy’s “peace mission” in Afghanistan

dsDescriptionValue.value:
Factors as culture, values and symbols are crucial to understand the 
evolution of the Italian foreign and defence policy. However, scholars’ 
attention to cultural variables in the study of Italian defence policies still leaves many gaps. This paper is a contribution towards closing such gap. Since the end of the Cold War Italian troops have been constantly engaged in military operations abroad spreading a “peacekeeper image” of Italy in the international arena. The aim of this work is to investigate the features and the evolution of the main strategic narratives 
adopted by political leaders to interpret the Italian military involvement in Afghanistan. How did politicians craft strategic narratives on the Afghan mission? How did these story lines influence public opinion during the conflict? How can we explain the drop of consensus occurred? In order to answer these questions this paper relies on polls and content analysis of parliamentary debates (2001-2011).
